The long-term trend in Homicides in Western Europe

Understanding how homicide rates have changed prior to the modern era requires the help of historians and archivists. Manuel Eisner, a criminology professor at the University of Cambridge, and his colleagues published the Historical Violence Database a compilation of data on long-term trends in homicide rates, in addition to qualitative information such as the cause of death, perpetrator and victim. This database is limited to countries with relatively complete historical records on violence and crime – mainly Western Europe and the US.

Starting in the second half of the nineteenth century, these European regions have consistent police records of those accused of murder or manslaughter and annual counts of homicide victims. To go back further in time, reaching as far back as the thirteenth century, Eisner collected estimates (from historical records of coroner reports, court trials, and the police) of homicide rates made in over ninety publications by scholars.

Homicide rates – measured as the number of homicides per 100,000 individuals – up to 1990 are sourced from Eisner’s (2003) publication and the Historical Violence Database.

Are homicide rates in Europe today lower or higher than in the past? Using the provided dataset, display and describe the long-run homicide rates for the five European regions: Italy, England, Germany, Netherlands and Scandinavia.

Western_Europe %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = homicides_per_100k, color = country))+ 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Homicide rates in Western Europe over time",
       x = "Year",
       y = "homicides Rate (per 100.000 peoples)",
       color = "Country")+
  theme_minimal()

Alright, the homicide rates should all be descending over time. What a comfort. But the viz is not super clear. Let’s check the rates for individual countries.

Western_Europe %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = homicides_per_100k, color = country))+ 
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Homicide rates in Western Europe over time",
       x = "Year",
       y = "homicides Rate (per 100.000 peoples)",
       color = "Country")+
  theme_minimal()+
  facet_wrap(~country,ncol=2)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 16,face="bold"),legend.position="bottom")

Compare the trends in homicide with the pattern of reign duration among Danish rulers through time.

  • Start a ggplot plotting midyear on x axis and duration on y axis
  • Try geom_smooth() for geometry
  • Provide meaningful labels and a title
  • How would you characterize the trend compared to the homicides above?
# YOUR CODE HERE:
library(readr)
kings <- read.csv("data/kings.csv",na="NULL")

kings %>%
  filter(!is.na(End_year),!is.na(Start_year)) %>% 
  mutate(duration=End_year- Start_year) %>% 
  mutate(midyear= End_year- duration/2) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=midyear,y=duration))+
  geom_smooth(color="hotpink")+
  labs(title="Reign-duration of Danish Kings over time",X="Midyear",Y="Reign-duration")

Final question:

In <250 words articulate your answer on the basis of the data visualisations to the following question:** are we more civilized today?** (Can you find an article or a book that discusses this topic?)

#In all of the graphs in the assignment “visualization” the graphs show a declining amount of homicides. It is therefore, arguable, from the data, that we have become more civilized. A lower amounts of homicides can indicate a higher amount of tolerance between peoples and nations, and hereby a more civilized society. However, drawing these conclusions from data concerning homicides only, can be misleading. Since homicides still exits in todays modern society (The war in Gaza or The war against Ukraine), and violence can be exercised in different forms, rather than the “primitive” way through homicide. Other complications arise, when discussing degree of civilization compared to amount of homicides. The semantics of the word “civilized” has been discussed, since the annotations associated with civilization, historically have been quite Eurocentric. It is therefore, imperative to associate the word with the moral implications linked to the assignment. We have laws which protect individual rights, bigger global cooperation and a better understanding of moral and ethics. However, looking at wars, inequality, destruction of environment and online-crime and -hate, it is arguable that further civilization, has not necessarily made humankind more morally correct or empathic. We still see displays of conflicts, abuse of power and social problems - they have simply changed forms.

#Reference to article: https://amnesty.dk/israels-regering-begaar-folkedrab-i-gaza-konkluderer-amnesty-international-i-en-ny-rapport/
